{"questionId":"35031907","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The diagram below shows a circular clockface with centre <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>O</mtext></math>. The clock’s minute hand has a length of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>. The clock’s hour hand has a length of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p>At <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>00</mn></math> pm the endpoint of the minute hand is at point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math> and the endpoint of the hour hand is at point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/9c00b7fec1733d7f6938f2b9781aed4a8888b645.png\"></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>00</mn></math> pm and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>13</mn></math> pm, the endpoint of the <strong>minute hand</strong> rotates through an angle, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi></math>, from point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math> to point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math>. This is illustrated in the diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/1aa7f950f45ad259e4c0596fc18e168f0d513266.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the size of angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi></math> in degrees.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>78</mn><mo>°</mo></math><em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"35031907","referenceCode":"21M.2.SL.TZ1.2c","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the size of angle θ in degrees.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.4—The circle, arc and area of sector, degrees only"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}